<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-511-634  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 511 634.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  May 28 1990 v9 n11 p66(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'No disclosure' in bid mix-up. (Army's Small Multiuser Computercontract)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. ArmyCompetitive BiddingDefense ContractsDisclosureLegal IssuesMinicomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>'No Disclosure' In Bid Mix-UpandM;Army contracting officials have determined that procurement documents weresent to the wrong company accidentally and there was no disclosure of onevendor's proposal to another.andM;Earlier this year, Army officials said bid documents intended for one companybidding for the Small Multiuser Computer (SMC) contract were shipped from theInformation Systems Command at Fort Huachuca, ARiz, to a competitor.andP;  ISCofficials were involved in evaluating the bids for the contract, which couldbe worth as much as $500 million.andM;An investigation was launched to determine how the mis-shipment occurred andto what extent the recipient of the bid examined the contents of the box[GCN, April 16].andM;Helen Garamone, a spokeswoman for the Information Systems Selection andAcquisition Agency, said officials at ISSAA in Alexandria, Va., and at FortHuachuca are satisfied that there were no improprieties in the mis-shipmentand that the recipient did not read the documents.andM;The incident added six weeks to the SMC evaluation, Garamone said.andP;  Lastyear, the program was delayed about six months while a contract protest wasadjudicated.andM;Under the SMC program, Army units might buy as many as 20,000 UNIXmini-computer systems.andP;  ISSAA will award the contract later this year, shesaid.andO;</TEXT></DOC>